## Step 0

Gather information about the Web3 application from the system document and component descriptions,
and its relationship with the properties above.
Use this information to inform how you plan to formalize them. Refer to the system document

## Step 1

Write a single CVL (Certora Verification Language) specification which formalizes all of the properties listed above.
Each property should have its own rule(s) or invariant(s) in the spec.

You are writing a CVL file without any implementation, neither for the contract being verified or
the other contracts mentioned as being interacted with.
However, you have been provided with the Solidity *interface* of these other contracts. If necessary,
you can write summaries in your specification file to capture the behavior of these other contracts' entry points.
If modeling the internal state of these other actors/contracts is necessary, use ghost state variables.
When setting up these summaries/ghosts, carefully consider whether the application will have multiple instances
of the implementation of the interface (`dynamic` or `multiple` sorts) or a single instance. In the former case,
your ghost state will need to account for the receiver contract.

If you need to model the state/behavior of an external actor (*not* one of the other explicit contracts in the system)
use the following decision procedure:
1. If the external actor is a permissioned role in the system, you can likely use permission accounting internal
   to your contract. For example, if the external actor is a singular admin role, you can request a stub field
   which holds the address of the administrator
2. If the external actor is an off-chain component, this behavior is not expressible in CVL, and 
   the property should be skipped
3. If the external actor is another contract not part of the application, you should use the summary/ghost approach
   described above. However, as there is no explicit interface provided for these external actor contracts you will
   need to make reasonable decisions about the summary signature to use.

To model the state/storage of the contract containing the component under verification,
you may use the stub tools described below. Do *NOT* try to simulate or otherwise model the
behavior/state of other contracts with state/functions in the contract you are verifying.

{% include "natspec_stub_tools_guidance.j2" %}

## Step 2

Invoke the advisory typecheck tool to ensure your specification is well-typed. If it is not, address
any feedback, and invoke the tool again. Otherwise, proceed to step 3.

## Step 3

Seek feedback on your specification from the feedback tool. If it indicates that your spec needs work, use
adaptive thinking to decide how to address its feedback, implement your changes, and reinvoke the tool until
it is satisfied with your specification.

The feedback judge is aware of all properties in this batch. It will flag missing coverage — if your spec
does not address a property and you have not declared a skip for it, the judge will reject your spec.
If you have declared a skip but the judge considers the justification insufficient, it will also reject
and may suggest how the property can in fact be formalized.

